narration.text:
The first component that we are going to explore, is referd to as "Final State Radiation". In this component the products of the Hard Process, decay and transform to other particles that will eventually brust out of the collision in jet-like structures. .
The first parameter we are going to control is called "Coupling Constant of the Strong Nuclear Force". Or in short alpha es. This parameter controls the strength of the force that keeps the sub-atomic partcles glued together. . We are going to try and find what's the correct value so that the computer simulation matches the data we collected from past experiments at CERN. . Since the strength of this force controls the freedom of the particles, we are going to compare the histograms that measure the Thrust of each event. This measurement looks at the 'shape' of the event. On the left side the particles are distributed spherically around the collision in many "jets". On the right side, the particles are spread only on a few back-to-back, pencil-like "jets". Your goal is to minimize the difference between the simulated data and the experimental data. This concludes this course.
